children.comment: Everything in Dart is an [Object].
children.name: Object

children.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all [Object]s is to return true if and
only if [:this:] and [other] are the same object.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override
the [hashCode] method as well to maintain consistency.
Returns a string representation of this object.
children.name: toString

children.comment:
[noSuchMethod] is invoked when users invoke a non-existant method
on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the
invocation are passed to [noSuchMethod] in an [Invocation].
If [noSuchMethod] returns a value, that value becomes the result of
the original invocation.

The default behavior of [noSuchMethod] is to throw a
[noSuchMethodError].
children.name: noSuchMethod

children.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the
same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality
operator [:==:]. Other than that there are no guarantees about
the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and
there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides [hashCode] it should override the
equality operator as well to maintain consistency.
children.name: hashCode

children.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.
children.name: runtimeType

children.comment:
Creates a new [Object] instance.

[Object] instances have no meaningful state, and are only useful
through their identity. An [Object] instance is equal to itself
only.
A single stack frame. Each frame points to a precise location in Dart code.
children.name: Frame

children.comment: Whether this stack frame comes from the Dart core libraries.
children.name: isCore

children.comment:
Returns a human-friendly description of the library that this stack frame
comes from.

This will usually be the string form of [uri], but a relative URI will be
used if possible.
children.name: library

children.comment:
Returns the name of the package this stack frame comes from, or `null` if
this stack frame doesn't come from a `package:` URL.
children.name: package

children.comment: A human-friendly description of the code location.
children.name: location

children.comment:
The URI of the file in which the code is located.

This URI will usually have the scheme `dart`, `file`, `http`, or `https`.
children.name: uri

children.comment:
The line number on which the code location is located.

This can be null, indicating that the line number is unknown or
unimportant.
children.name: line

children.comment:
The column number of the code location.

This can be null, indicating that the column number is unknown or
unimportant.
children.name: column

children.comment:
The name of the member in which the code location occurs.

Anonymous closures are represented as `<fn>` in this member string.
children.name: member

children.comment:
Returns a single frame of the current stack.

By default, this will return the frame above the current method. If
[level] is `0`, it will return the current method's frame; if [level] is
higher than `1`, it will return higher frames.
children.name: caller

children.comment: Parses a string representation of a Dart VM stack frame.
children.name: parseVM

children.comment: Parses a string representation of a Chrome/V8 stack frame.
children.name: parseV8

children.comment: Parses a string representation of a Firefox stack frame.
children.name: parseFirefox

children.comment: Parses this package's string representation of a stack frame.
children.name: parseFriendly
